notesStmt.note: This is an illustrated and illuminated composite volume of three poetic texts: the Khamsah (quintet) of Niẓāmī Ganjavī (d. 605 AH / 1209 CE), the Khamsah (quintet) of Amīr Khusraw Dihlavī (d. 725 AH / 1325 CE), and the Timūrnāmah (Epic of Timur) by ʿAbd Allāh Hātifī (d. 927 AH / 1520 CE), also known as the Ẓafarnāmah. The texts are written in black naskh script, with titles, section headings, and incidentals in white or red tawqīʿ/riqāʿ script. It was produced in the tenth century AH / sixteenth CE, in either India or Safavid Iran. The binding is not original to the manuscript. According to a note on front flyleaf iia, the codex was re-bound and restored by a bookbinder of Tabriz, Khwand Mullā Mahdī Ṣaḥḥāf-i Tabrīzī in 1295 AH /1878 CE.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Persian.

msItem.title: Khamsah-i Niẓāmī
خمسه نظامي
msItem.incipit: بسم الله الرحمن الرحيم هست كليد در كنج حكيم...
msItem.note: Written in main text area (four columns); contains all five poems: Makhzan al-asrār, Khusraw va Shīrīn, Laylá va Majnūn, Haft paykar, and Iskandarnāmah (divided into Iqbālnāmah and Khidrnāmah)

msItem.title: Khamsah-i Dihlavī
خمسه دهلوى
msItem.incipit: بسم الله الرحمن الرحيم خطبه قدست بملك قديم...
msItem.note: Obliquely written text placed in the outer area within the frame and in the first column; contains Maṭlaʿ al-anvār, Shīrin va Khusraw, Majnūn va Laylá, Āyinah-i Iskandarī, and Hasht bihisht; blank spaces and some missing couplets on fols. 175a-175b

support.p: Tinted laid paper: cream for text area and rose or light brown for margins

p.catchwords: Written obliquely at ends of fifth columns

layoutDesc.layout: Written surface within frame consisting of five columns, the first with text written obliquely, as well as a margin, also with obliquely written text; text of Khamsah-i Niẓāmī begins in second column; framing lines in orange, green, gold, black, and white
Obliquely written text beginning in the outer area of fol. 282b and continuing in the first column (after fol. 316a occupying the other columns as well)

handDesc.handNote: Main text written in small naskh script executed in black ink; titles of works and other inscriptions in headpieces and subheadings in tawqīʿ/riqāʿ script in white or red ink

decoDesc.decoNote: Illustrations; double-page illuminated frontispiece (right side now missing); incipit pages with headpieces; titlepieces introducing various works plus smaller pieces; blank spaces and some couplets missing on fols. 175a-175b
Illustrations; various works introduced by small illuminated titlepieces
Illustrations; illuminated rectangular piece occupying the outer area and the first column with the inscription: Tamarnāmah-i [sic] Hātifī ʿalayhi al-raḥmah

decoNote.title: Double-page illuminated frontispiece with titlepiece
decoNote.note: This is the left side of a double-page illuminated frontispiece, inscribed in the central panel with the titles of the three works contained in the manuscript, as well as their locations within the frame. The facing page is now missing.

decoNote.title: Incipit with illuminated titlepiece
decoNote.note: This illuminated titlepiece is inscribed in white tawqīʿ/riqāʿ script: Makhzan al-asrār-i Shaykh-i Niẓāmī ʿalayhi al-raḥmah. Three small triangular pieces at the beginning of the text introduce Maṭlaʿ al-anwār, the first poem of the Khamsah of Dihlavī. There is one cornerpiece with floral design.

decoNote.title: An old woman implores Sultan Sanjar for help
decoNote.note: An old woman complains before Sultan Sanjar on horseback about feeling oppressed by his policeman.

decoNote.title: Incipit with illuminated headpiece and titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has two illuminated pieces, a headpiece and a titlepiece. The latter is in the lower panel, which is inscribed: Khusraw va Shīrīn-i Shaykh-i Niẓāmī.

decoNote.title: Khusraw watching Shīrīn bathing
Incipit with illuminated headpiece and titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has a few illuminated pieces. Above, there is a headpiece inscribed: huwa Allāh. At the right is a triangular piece and the inscription: Shīrin va Khusraw-i Amīr Khusraw.

decoNote.title: Shīrīn visiting Farhād at Mt. Bisitūn
Shīrīn rides out to Bisitūn
Shīrīn on horseback giving a drink to Farhād
Illustrated finispiece with three men praying near a stream
decoNote.note: This illustrated finispiece depicts three men praying by a stream. The scene makes reference to the final verses (a prayer) that conclude Khusraw va Shīrīn.

decoNote.title: Incipit with illuminated headpiece and titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has an illuminated headpiece and, in the lower panel, a titlepiece inscribed Laylá va Majnūn.

decoNote.title: Laylá and Majnūn at school
Incipit with illuminated headpiece and titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has an illuminated headpiece and titlepiece. Above is a two-tiered illumination inscribed Allāhu wa-lā siwāhu. Below, at the right, are two small rectagular pieces insscribed: Majnūn Laylá-i Amīr Khusraw.

decoNote.title: Nawfal’s battle with Laylá’s tribe
Laylá and Majnūn meet in the desert
Sick woman in bed with her attendants
Incipit with illuminated headpiece and titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has an illuminated titepiece inscribed: Haft paykar-i Shaykh-i Niẓāmī in white ink.

decoNote.title: King enthroned in a landscape receiving gifts
Incipit with illuminated titlepiece
decoNote.note: This illuminated incipit page has a large titlepiece inscribed: huwa Allāhu subḥānahu. On the right side, below the titlepiece, three triangles are inscribed: Hasht bihisht-i Amīr Khusraw.

Incipit with illuminated headpiece and titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has several illuminated pieces. The titlepiece is inscribed: Iqbālnāmah-i Iskandarī.

decoNote.title: Incipit with illuminated headpiece and titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has several illuminated pieces. In the illuminated panels at the lower right is inscribed: Āyinah-i Iskandarī-i Amīr Khusraw.

decoNote.title: Alexander the Great (Iskandar) fighting the Zanghis (Ethiopians)
Illustrated finispiece with landscape
Incipit with illuminated headpiece and titlepiece
decoNote.note: This incipit page has a number of illuminated pieces, including a titlepiece inscribed: Khirdnāmah-i Iskandari-i Niẓāmī.

decoNote.title: Incipit with illuminated pieces
decoNote.note: This illuminated incipit page has a headpiece in the form of a dome and two rectangular pieces below, one of which is a tailpiece for the end of Khamsah-i Amīr Khusraw; the other has the inscription: Timurnāmah-i Hātifī ʿalayhi al-raḥmah.

decoNote.title: Alexander the Great (Iskandar) being handed a letter that describes a dangerous passage through the mountains
Illustrated finispiece
decoNote.note: This is the right side of a double-page illustrated finispiece.

decoNote.title: Illustrated finispiece
decoNote.note: This is the left side of a double-page illustrated finispiece. A youthful prince in a landscape is depicted dictating a letter.

binding.p: Red leather with central medallion, pendants, and cornerpieces (no flap); gold-painted arabesque decoration; re-bound and restored by a bookbinder of Tabriz, Khwand Mullā Mahdī Ṣaḥḥāf-i Tabrīzī (see note, signed and dated 1295 AH / 1878 CE on front flyleaf iia)

origin.origDate: 10th century AH / 16th CE; partial dates given on fol. 26a (last day of Ramaḍān) and fol. 214b (Shawwāl)

history.provenance: Note regarding re-binding and restoration of this volume by a bookbinder of Tabriz, Khwand Mullā Mahdī Ṣaḥḥāf-i Tabrīzī, signed and dated 1295 AH / 1878 CE (front flyleaf iia)
Seal impression with motto containing the name Munḏir (fol. 280b)
